# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: banana-pudding
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] Fried plantain is also eaten in some countries in South America and the Caribbean where African influence is present.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] For example in the Dominican Republic, Nicaragua, Puerto Rico and to a lesser extent Cuba, it is common to cut plantains into slices, fry them until they are yellow, smash them between two plates and fry them again.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] Puerto Rico has *mofongo*, a dish consisting of fried and pounded plantains with *chicharrón*, spices, fat (butter, lard or olive oil) and usually in a broth or served with meat, seafood on top or on the side.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] This is also a common dish in Haiti, referred to as *bannann peze*, and throughout Central America, referred to as *patacones* in Costa Rica, Panama, Colombia and Ecuador, and as *tostones* in Nicaragua and the Spanish-speaking Caribbean.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] In Honduras and Venezuela they are referred to as *tajadas*.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] Puerto Rico also has *arañitas* (spiders), where green and yellow plantains are shredded together, seasoned, shaped into patties then fried until crisp.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] Other traditional fried plantain dishes in Puerto Rico include *alcapurria*, *pionono*, *ralleno de amarillo* (similar to *papa rellena* but made with yellow plantain instead of potato), and *bolitas de plátano* (plantain dumplings).
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] Fried plantain may be served as a snack, a starter or a side dish to the main course, such as with Jollof rice, spicy barbecued meat, tomato stew or beans.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] It is made in different ways: salted or unsalted, cut into "ears" or "fingers", diced or fried whole.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] In the Spanish-speaking Caribbean fried green plantains are eaten with mojo sauce in Cuba and Puerto Rico and wasakaka in the Dominican Republic, both a wet savory garlic sauce.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] They are sometimes eaten with ketchup or a mayonnaise-ketchup mixture.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] In the Pacific city of Cali, Colombia, plantains are eaten fried and accompanied by a condiment called Hogao.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] Sweet plantains are also served with savory entrees in the Caribbean, especially the Spanish-speaking islands, Pacific Colombia and Jamaica.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] Gizdodo is a side dish in Nigeria containing fried plantain and grilled gizzard.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] This traditional snack has a long history and is cherished for its delightful taste and simplicity.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] They are a staple in Yoruba cuisine and is enjoyed by people of all ages across Nigeria.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] To prepare *ipekere*, ripe plantains are peeled and sliced into thin, uniform shapes, typically using a knife or a mandoline slicer.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] These are deep-fried until they turn golden brown, resulting in a crunchy and slightly sweet snack.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] They can also be flavoured with different spices, such as cayenne pepper, ginger, onion powder, or garlic powder.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] Some people also fry onions and fresh ginger along with the plantain slices for added flavour.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] The plantains are peeled and may be cut into chunks or cubes.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] Ginger, cayenne pepper, and salt are the typical spices used to make *kelewele.* Onions, anise, cloves, nutmeg, cinnamon, and chili powder, however, may also be used as spices.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] Commercial preparations exist that can simplify preparation and offer a standardized taste.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] The oil should be hot and the plantain should not be too soft or it will absorb too much oil.
[src:banana-pudding/alloco] The plantain should be fried until the sugar in it caramelizes, and produces brown edges on the plantain.
[src:banana-pudding/american-public-media] Formerly, much of American Public Media's programming content was distributed by Public Radio International, which itself was named American Public Radio, or APR, until July 1, 1994.
[src:banana-pudding/american-public-media] APR was formed by four stations—the Minnesota Public Radio network, WGBH in Boston, WNYC in New York, and KUSC in Los Angeles—to distribute *A Prairie Home Companion*.
[src:banana-pudding/american-public-media] PRI owns and produces numerous programs today, but still also distributes diverse programming from many sources.
[src:banana-pudding/american-public-media] The split happened as MPR and PRI began seeing each other more as potential competitors after MPR lost the partnership to WGBH to produce *The World*, and MPR purchased PRI-distributed *Marketplace* for its own distribution channels.
[src:banana-pudding/american-public-media] In 2020 the Lab began publishing a project called Color of Coronavirus that tracks deaths due to COVID-19 by race and ethnicity in each U.S. state as well as the nation as a whole.
[src:banana-pudding/american-public-media] This project has been cited hundreds of times, including by The Guardian, The Atlantic, Newsweek, The Washington Post, The New York Times, and the Journal of the American Medical Association.
[src:banana-pudding/american-public-media] Until July 2015, APM operated Classical South Florida (WMLV-FM 89.7), which was sold to Educational Media Foundation, a California-based religious broadcasting company that airs contemporary Christian music; it now brands itself as a K-Love station.
[src:banana-pudding/american-public-media] Several specials are also distributed by APM on a less frequent basis, including a number of Christmas programs, *Giving Thanks* at Thanksgiving, and the *BBC Proms*.
[src:banana-pudding/annin-tofu] The name "tofu" here refers to "tofu-like solid"; soy beans, which are the main ingredient of tofu, are not used, nor coagulated as soybeans would be to make tofu.
[src:banana-pudding/annin-tofu] This naming convention is also seen in other East Asian dishes, such as Chinese *yúdòufu* (魚豆腐) and Japanese *gomadōfu* (胡麻豆腐).
[src:banana-pudding/annin-tofu] Apricot kernel milk is often confused with almond milk, as apricot kernel itself is often confused with almond.
[src:banana-pudding/annin-tofu] In the traditional recipe, the primary flavoring agent is apricot kernels, soaked and ground with water.
[src:banana-pudding/annin-tofu] The mixture is strained, sweetened, and heated with a gelling agent (usually agar).
[src:banana-pudding/annin-tofu] When chilled, the apricot kernel milk mixture solidifies into the consistency of a soft gelatin dessert.
[src:banana-pudding/annin-tofu] Although the agar-based recipe is vegan, there are numerous nontraditional recipes that are not.
[src:banana-pudding/annin-tofu] Most are based on dairy products and a small amount of flavored extract.
[src:banana-pudding/annin-tofu] Gelatin is also a common substitute for agar.
[src:banana-pudding/annin-tofu] Annin jelly can be made from scratch or using instant mix.
[src:banana-pudding/annin-tofu] There is an instant soy-based powder with a coagulating agent, which dissolves in hot water and solidifies upon cooling.
[src:banana-pudding/annin-tofu] In Taiwanese cuisine, the dish uses the sweeter southern variety of apricot kernels which are mixed with peanuts.
[src:banana-pudding/annin-tofu] In Taipei, the dessert originated as a food stall dish, but is now also served in banquets halls and hotel restaurants.
[src:banana-pudding/annin-tofu] In Hawaii where it is commonly known as "almond float," it was introduced by Chinese immigrants starting in the 1850s, it is now usually made with gelatin and almond extract and typically mixed with canned fruit cocktail and canned lychee.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] In the Balkans and Turkey, Muslims make the dish during the month of Muharram in which the Day of Ashura takes place.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Armenians make it as a Christmas pudding and for New Year's celebrations, where it is a centerpiece, Sephardic Jews prepare the dish to celebrate the Jewish holiday of Tu BiShvat.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] In some Jewish, Christian, and Muslim traditions, a similar dish is prepared to commemorate a child's first tooth, or the passing of a family member.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] For the people of the ancient Near East, foods composed of boiled whole grains came to be associated with spring and harvest rites since ancient times.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] This association spread to Asia, Europe, and Africa.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Rites related with Tammuz, the Babylonian god of wheat and fertility, were recorded as late as the 10th century by an Arab traveler who wrote about boiled wheat among the dishes consumed at a pagan celebration held at Harran.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Jews, Christians and Muslims have all consumed boiled wheat in a variety of ways under various names for millennia.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] These dishes have been sweetened in various ways with sugar, fruit molasses, and dried fruits.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] According to one tradition, it is claimed that when the ark came to rest on Mount Ararat, the family of Noah celebrated with a special dish.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Since their supplies were nearly exhausted, what was left (primarily grains, dried fruits and the like) was cooked together to form a pudding and that "pudding" is now called *anoushabour*.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Armenians make anoushabur to commemorate this event, but also other events.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] After a baby is born, Armenian families observe a period of seclusion for up to 40 days, culminating in a baptism ceremony (knunk).
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] In general, Armenians enjoy anoushabur as a part of festive spreads.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Armenian sources note it was cleverly used to maintain the fast, yet celebrate Christmas eve with a sweet treat.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] It’s also used in thanksgiving offerings, during weddings or house blessings.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Sharing Anoushabur is a gesture of communal warmth, linking family, faith, and gratitude.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Anoushabur is distributed to the poor, as well as to neighbors, friends and relatives.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Since Armenians serve this pudding during Christmas (6 January) and on New Year's Eve (Armenians of Jerusalem celebrate it at 13 January), it is sometimes called "Armenian Christmas Pudding".
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] This traditional Armenian sweet porridge is made from wheat or barley, dried fruits (such as apricots, raisins, and prunes), sugar, spices (like vanilla and cinnamon) and nuts (almonds and pistachios are most common).
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] The grains are simmered until tender, then combined with the fruits and nuts, then sweetened, and flavored with rose water and the spices.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Anoushabur may be garnished with pomegranate seeds, dried fruits and cinnamon.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] The pudding may be accompanied by multiple Armenian desserts and nuts, such as almonds or pistachios.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Anoushabur (անուշապուր) is a compound Armenian word.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] "Anoush" (անուշ) means sweet and "Abur" (ապուր) means soup or porridge, so the word Anoushabur literally means "Sweet soup" or "Sweet porridge".
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] According to one tradition, it is claimed that when the ark came to rest on Mount Cudi or Mount Ararat, the family of Nuh or Noah celebrated with a special dish.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Since their supplies were nearly exhausted, what was left (primarily grains, dried fruits and the like) was cooked together to form a pudding, what is now called *ashure*.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Turkish families make ashure pudding to commemorate this event.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Ashure is distributed to the poor, as well as to neighbors, friends and relatives.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] According to a late Ottoman writer, passages from the Quran were spoken over the cauldron of cooked aşure in memory of deceased family members before it was served to neighbors, suggesting that for certain Sunni families the meal had a connection to remembering the deceased.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Today, a dish akin to this is prepared to honor a child's first tooth.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] According to the Ottoman historian Ahmed Cavid (d.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] 1803), women gave it away to loved ones, friends, and the impoverished as a gesture of gratitude for the child's survival of the difficult first year of life.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] In Turkey and many other Middle Eastern countries, this tradition is still common among Christians, Jews, and Muslims.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] The dish can be either sweet or savory and is known in Turkey as diş buğday ('tooth wheat').
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Aşure is also made during the Hıdırellez spring celebration, which is the occasion where it is most similar to its ancient pagan roots.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Sephardic Jews prepare Ashure, also known as "*trigo koço*", for the Jewish holiday of Tu BiShvat.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] It is made out of boiling wheat grains combined with sugar, crushed walnuts, and cinnamon.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] According to Aylin Öney Tan, this practice may have originated from early Jewish communities in Anatolia during the Byzantine period rather than being brought to Ottoman Turkey by Sephardic Jews who settled there following their expulsion from Spain and Portugal in the late 15th century.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Several Jewish communities prepare Ashura, also known as *b'Lila*, to celebrate a child's first tooth.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] This dish is prepared in Bosnia and Bulgaria under the names hašure and ashoure, respectively.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Ashure porridge does not have a single recipe, as recipes vary between regions and families.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Traditionally, it is said to have at least seven ingredients.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Some say at least ten ingredients must be used, in keeping with the theme of "tenth", while Alevis always use twelve.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Among these are wheat, barley, rice, white beans, chickpeas, pekmez, date molasses, pomegranate molasses, beet juice, dried fruits like dates, raisins, currants, apricots, figs, apples and nuts like pistachios, almonds, hazelnuts, walnuts, pine nuts and sesame seeds.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] However, many renditions add orange, lemon and lime peel to add depth to the pudding.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] Anise seed, black cumin seeds, prunus mahaleb, pomegranate arils, cardamom, cinnamon, cloves, nutmeg, allspice and desiccated or shredded coconut may be used as garnish, and some variations are flavored with anise liqueur, rose water and/or orange blossom water.
[src:banana-pudding/ashure] The word Ashure comes from the Arabic word "Ashura" (Arabic: عَاشُوْرَاء **ʿĀshūrāʾ**), meaning 'tenth'.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] Asida is particularly common in Sudan, Morocco, Libya, Algeria, Tunisia, Yemen, Ethiopia, Eritrea, and the rest of the Middle East.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] Often served during religious holidays such as Mawlid and Eid, it is also served during other traditional ceremonies—for example, those accompanying the birth of a child, such as the *‘aqīqah*, the cutting of the hair of a newborn seven days after birth.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] A simple, yet rich dish, often eaten without other complementary dishes, it is traditionally served at breakfast and is also given to women in labor.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] The name *asida* is derived from the Arabic root عصد (ʿ-ṣ-d), associated with twisting or kneading.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] One of the earliest documented recipes for asida is found in a tenth century Arabic cookbook by Ibn Sayyar al-Warraq called *Kitab al-Ṭabīḫ* (Arabic: كتاب الطبيخ, *The Book of Dishes*).
[src:banana-pudding/asida] It was described as a thick pudding of dates cooked with clarified butter (*samn*).
[src:banana-pudding/asida] A recipe for asida was also mentioned in an anonymous Hispano-Muslim cookbook dating to the 13th century.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] In the 13th and 14th centuries, in the mountainous region of the Rif along the Mediterranean coast of Morocco, a flour made from lightly grilled barley was used in place of wheat flour.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] A recipe for asida that adds argan seed oil was documented by Leo Africanus (c.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] 1465–1550), the Arab explorer known as Hasan al-Wazan in the Arab world.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] According to the French scholar Maxime Rodinson, asida were typical foods among the Bedouin of pre-Islamic and, probably, later times.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] In the old city of Fez, vendors sell squares of cold semolina pudding sprinkled with sugar and cinnamon, usually consumed by children after school.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] The Libyan variation of asida is served with a sweet syrup, usually date or carob syrup (rub), but also with honey, as well as melted butter around the asida itself.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] Asida (Aseeda) is made primarily as a dessert by Palestinians.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] It serves as a both a comfort food and a dish to mark special occasions.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] The dessert version is served with honey or date syrup, and for special occasions might see the addition of sauteed nuts and cinnamon.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] A savory dish also called asida but consisting of stewed wheat berries with lamb is made in at least one village in Palestine at times of mourning, attesting to the uniqueness and specificity of local food customs.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] The Tunisian version of this dish is served with either a mixture of honey and butter or a hot chili pepper paste (harissa).
[src:banana-pudding/asida] The latter is more common later in the day and the former earlier.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] Asida is also commonly consumed with carob syrup or date syrup in southern parts of Tunisia.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] Aseedah or aseed (Arabic: عصيدة) is one of the staple dishes in Yemen and is usually served for lunch, dinner, or breakfast.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] Its ingredients include wholemeal wheat, boiling water, and salt as needed.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] A pot of water is placed on high heat until boiling.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] Slowly, handfuls of wholemeal wheat are added and then mixed quickly with a large wooden spoon to avoid forming lumps.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] The process is repeated until the mixture is thick.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] Traditionally the cook lowers the pot to the floor where they hold the pot with their feet and stir vigorously.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] Finally, the hot, steaming dough is shaped using bare oiled hands and usually placed in a wide, wooden bowl.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] Sometimes a depression is made in the middle of the shaped aseedah into which a hot chili tomato paste can be added or helba, a fenugreek mixture made with parsley and garlic.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] Lamb or a chicken stock is then poured around the aseedah.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] Aseedah can also be made using white, bleached wheat.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] Honey can be used instead of stock and chili/helba.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] It is a meal, using only boiled water, flour, and some salt.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] Typically it is smothered in beef soup or chicken or even lamb.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] It is usually served hot and eaten with hands or spoons.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] Aseed is eaten particularly at lunchtime and during Ramadan.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] The Ethiopian version of this dish is called genfo in Amharic.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] It is served with Ethiopian ghee (called niter kibbeh), berbere (an Ethiopian spice mix), yogurt, or even milk.
[src:banana-pudding/asida] It is popular during Ramadan, and is often served with a meat-and-tomato sauce.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] A **banana** is an elongated, edible fruit that is botanically a berry produced by several kinds of large treelike herbaceous flowering plants in the genus *Musa*.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In some countries, cooking bananas are called plantains, distinguishing them from **dessert bananas**.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The fruit is variable in size, color and firmness, but is usually elongated and curved, with soft flesh rich in starch covered with a peel, which may have a variety of colors when ripe.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] It grows upward in clusters near the top of the plant.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Almost all modern edible seedless (parthenocarp) cultivated bananas come from two wild species – *Musa acuminata* and *Musa balbisiana*, or their hybrids.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Worldwide, there is no sharp distinction between dessert "bananas" and cooking "plantains": this distinction works well enough in the Americas and Europe, but it breaks down in Southeast Asia where many more kinds of bananas are grown and eaten.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The term "banana" is applied also to other members of the *Musa* genus, such as the scarlet banana (*Musa coccinea*), the pink banana (*Musa velutina*), and the Fe'i bananas.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Members of the genus *Ensete*, such as the snow banana (*Ensete glaucum*) and the economically important false banana (*Ensete ventricosum*) of Africa are sometimes included.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Both genera are in the banana family, Musaceae.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Banana plantations can be damaged by parasitic nematodes and insect pests, and to fungal and bacterial diseases, one of the most serious being Panama disease which is caused by a *Fusarium* fungus.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] This and black sigatoka threaten the production of Cavendish bananas, the main kind eaten in the Western world, which is a triploid *Musa acuminata*.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Plant breeders are seeking new varieties, but these are difficult to breed given that commercial varieties are seedless.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] To enable future breeding, banana germplasm is conserved in multiple gene banks around the world.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The banana plant is the largest herbaceous flowering plant.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] All the above-ground parts of a banana plant grow from a structure called a corm.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Plants are normally tall and fairly sturdy with a tree-like appearance, but what appears to be a trunk is actually a pseudostem composed of multiple leaf-stalks (petioles).
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Bananas grow in a wide variety of soils, as long as it is at least 60 centimetres (2.0 ft) deep, has good drainage and is not compacted.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] They are fast-growing plants, with a growth rate of up to 1.6 metres (5.2 ft) per day.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The leaves of banana plants are composed of a stalk (petiole) and a blade (lamina).
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The base of the petiole widens to form a sheath; the tightly packed sheaths make up the pseudostem, which is all that supports the plant.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The edges of the sheath meet when it is first produced, making it tubular.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] As new growth occurs in the centre of the pseudostem, the edges are forced apart.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Cultivated banana plants vary in height depending on the variety and growing conditions.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Most are around 5 m (16 ft) tall, with a range from 'Dwarf Cavendish' plants at around 3 m (9.8 ft) to 'Gros Michel' at 7 m (23 ft) or more.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Leaves are spirally arranged and may grow 2.7 metres (8.9 ft) long and 60 cm (2.0 ft) wide.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] When a banana plant is mature, the corm stops producing new leaves and begins to form a flower spike or inflorescence.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] A stem develops which grows up inside the pseudostem, carrying the immature inflorescence until eventually it emerges at the top.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Each pseudostem normally produces a single inflorescence, also known as the "banana heart".
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] After fruiting, the pseudostem dies, but offshoots will normally have developed from the base, so that the plant as a whole is perennial.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The inflorescence contains many petal-like bracts between rows of flowers.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The female flowers (which can develop into fruit) appear in rows further up the stem (closer to the leaves) from the rows of male flowers.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The ovary is inferior, meaning that the tiny petals and other flower parts appear at the tip of the ovary.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The banana fruits develop from the *banana heart*, in a large hanging cluster called a *bunch*, made up of around nine tiers called *hands*, with up to 20 fruits to a hand.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The stalk ends of the fruits connect up to the rachis part of the inflorescence.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Opposite the stalk end, is the blossom end, where the remnants of the flower deviate the texture from the rest of the flesh inside the peel.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The fruit has been described as a "leathery berry".
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] There is a protective outer layer (a peel or skin) with numerous long, thin strings (Vascular bundles), which run lengthwise between the skin and the edible inner white flesh.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The peel is less palatable and usually discarded after peeling the fruit.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The inner part of the common yellow dessert variety can be split lengthwise into three sections that correspond to the inner portions of the three carpels by manually deforming the unopened fruit.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In cultivated varieties, fertile seeds are usually absent.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] A 2011 phylogenomic analysis using nuclear genes indicates the phylogeny of some representatives of the Musaceae family.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Major edible kinds of banana are shown in **boldface**.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Work by Li and colleagues in 2024 identifies three subspecies of *M. acuminata*, namely sspp.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] *banksii*, *malaccensis*, and *zebrina*, as contributing substantially to the *Ban*, *Dh*, and *Ze* subgenomes of triploid cultivated bananas respectively.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The genus *Musa* was created by Carl Linnaeus in 1753.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The name may be derived from Antonius Musa, physician to the Emperor Augustus, or Linnaeus may have adapted the Arabic word for banana, *mauz*.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The word "banana" is thought to be of West African origin, possibly from the Wolof word *banaana*, and passed into English via Spanish or Portuguese.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The classification of cultivated bananas has long been a problematic issue for taxonomists.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Linnaeus originally placed bananas into two species based only on their uses as food: *Musa sapientum* for dessert bananas and *Musa paradisiaca* for plantains.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] More species names were added, but this approach proved to be inadequate for the number of cultivars in the primary center of diversity of the genus, Southeast Asia.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Many of these cultivars were given names that were later discovered to be synonyms.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In a series of papers published from 1947 onward, Ernest Cheesman showed that Linnaeus's *Musa sapientum* and *Musa paradisiaca* were cultivars and descendants of two wild seed-producing species, *Musa acuminata* and *Musa balbisiana*, both first described by Luigi Aloysius Colla.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Researchers Norman Simmonds and Ken Shepherd proposed a genome-based nomenclature system in 1955.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] This system eliminated almost all the difficulties and inconsistencies of the earlier classification of bananas based on assigning scientific names to cultivated varieties.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Despite this, the original names are still recognized by some authorities, leading to confusion.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The accepted scientific names for most groups of cultivated bananas are *Musa acuminata* Colla and *Musa balbisiana* Colla for the ancestral species, and *Musa* × *paradisiaca* L. for the hybrid of the two.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] An unusual feature of the genetics of the banana is that chloroplast DNA is inherited maternally, while mitochondrial DNA is inherited paternally.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] This facilitates taxonomic study of species and subspecies relationships.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In regions such as North America and Europe, *Musa* fruits offered for sale can be divided into small sweet "bananas" eaten raw when ripe as a dessert, and large starchy "plantains" or cooking bananas, which do not have to be ripe.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Linnaeus made this distinction when naming two "species" of *Musa*.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Members of the "plantain subgroup" of banana cultivars, most important as food in West Africa and Latin America, correspond to this description, having long pointed fruit.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] They are described by Ploetz et al. as "true" plantains, distinct from other cooking bananas.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The cooking bananas of East Africa belong to a different group, the East African Highland bananas.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Further, small farmers in Colombia grow a much wider range of cultivars than large commercial plantations do, and in Southeast Asia—the center of diversity for bananas, both wild and cultivated—the distinction between "bananas" and "plantains" does not work.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Many bananas are used both raw and cooked.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] There are starchy cooking bananas which are smaller than those eaten raw.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The range of colors, sizes and shapes is far wider than in those grown or sold in Africa, Europe or the Americas.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Southeast Asian languages do not make the distinction between "bananas" and "plantains" that is made in English.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Thus both Cavendish dessert bananas and Saba cooking bananas are called *pisang* in Malaysia and Indonesia, *kluai* in Thailand and *chuối* in Vietnam.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Fe'i bananas, grown and eaten in the islands of the Pacific, are derived from a different wild species.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Most Fe'i bananas are cooked, but Karat bananas, which are short and squat with bright red skins, are eaten raw.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The earliest domestication of bananas (*Musa* spp.) was from naturally occurring parthenocarpic (seedless) individuals of *Musa banksii* in New Guinea.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] These were cultivated by Papuans before the arrival of Austronesian-speakers.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Numerous phytoliths of bananas have been recovered from the Kuk Swamp archaeological site and dated to around 10,000 to 6,500 BP.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Foraging humans in this area began domestication in the late Pleistocene using transplantation and early cultivation methods.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Various investigations – including Denham *et al.*, 2003 – determine that by the early to middle of the Holocene the process was complete.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] From New Guinea, cultivated bananas spread westward into Island Southeast Asia.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] They hybridized with other (possibly independently domesticated) subspecies of *Musa acuminata* as well as *M. balbisiana* in the Philippines, northern New Guinea, and possibly Halmahera.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] These hybridization events produced the triploid cultivars of bananas commonly grown today.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] From Island Southeast Asia, they became part of the staple domesticated crops of the Austronesian peoples and were spread via their ancient seaborne migrations and ancient maritime trading routes into Oceania, Africa, South Asia, and Indochina.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Bananas are believed to have been introduced to Africa from Southeast Asia via the Austronesian settlement of Madagascar (c.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] However, the role of Madagascar as a staging board for the dispersal of bananas (and other Asian crops) is unclear.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Malagasy people colonized Madagascar from Island Southeast Asia around 600 AD onwards, but contact between East Africa and Island Southeast Asia dates back to at least 300 BC or earlier.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The possibility that bananas may have been introduced from earlier Austronesian settlements in the East African coast that pre-date the settlement of Madagascar can not be ruled out.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] These ancient introductions resulted in the banana subgroup now known as the "true" plantains, which include the East African Highland bananas and the Pacific plantains (the Iholena and Maoli-Popo'ulu subgroups).
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Genetic evidence show that East African Highland bananas (AAA) originated from banana populations introduced to Africa from the region between Java, Borneo, and New Guinea.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Pacific plantains (AAB), on the other hand, were introduced to the Pacific Islands from banana populations originating from either eastern New Guinea or the Bismarck Archipelago.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Another wave of introductions later spread domesticated polyploid bananas to other parts of tropical Asia, particularly Indochina and the Indian subcontinent.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Southeast Asia remains the region of primary diversity of the banana.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Areas of secondary diversity are found in Africa, indicating a long history of banana cultivation there.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] 21st century discoveries of alleged banana phytoliths in Uganda and Cameroon dating to the first millennium BC and earlier triggered a debate about the date of the first introduction of bananas to East Africa.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] However, the identification of the remains in Uganda as phytoliths, much less banana phytoliths, is now considered dubious.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The Cameroon phytoliths, on the other hand, are confirmed as *Musa*, despite early doubts that they may be from *Ensete*.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] An introduction date of 2000 to 1000 BC is also unlikely as this was long before there were any evidence of agriculture in East Africa.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Polyploid banana cultivars are sterile and do not spread without human cultivation.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Similarly, phytoliths recovered from the Kot Diji archaeological site in Pakistan were interpreted as evidence that bananas were known to the Indus Valley civilisation.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] This may indicate very early dispersal of bananas by Austronesian traders by sea from as early as 2000 BCE.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] But this is still putative, as they may have come from local wild *Musa* species used for fiber or as ornamentals, not food; and banana phytoliths are absent in other contemporary sites in South Asia.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Glucanase and two other proteins specific to Musaceae were found in dental calculus from the early Iron Age (12th century BCE) Philistines in Tel Erani in the southern Levant.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] However, the authors only tentatively identify it as *Musa*, as the proteins can also be found in *Ensete* (cultivated for their edible corms and pseudostems in Africa).
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The banana may have been present in isolated locations in the Middle East on the eve of Islam.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The spread of Islam was followed by far-reaching diffusion.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] There are numerous references to it in Islamic texts (such as poems and hadiths) from the 9th century onwards.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] By the 10th century, the banana appeared in texts from Palestine and Egypt.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] From there, it diffused into North Africa and Al-Andalus (Islamic Spain) during the Arab Agricultural Revolution.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] An article on banana tree cultivation is included in Ibn al-'Awwam's 12th-century agricultural work, *Kitāb al-Filāḥa* (*Book on Agriculture*).
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] During the Middle Ages, bananas from Granada were considered among the best in the Arab world.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Bananas were certainly grown in the Christian Kingdom of Cyprus by the late medieval period.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Writing in 1458, the Italian traveller and writer Gabriele Capodilista wrote favourably of the extensive farm produce of the estates at Episkopi, near modern-day Limassol, including the area's banana plantations.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In the early modern period, bananas were encountered by European explorers during the Magellan expedition in 1521, in both Guam and the Philippines.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Lacking a name for the fruit, the ship's historian Antonio Pigafetta described them as "figs more than one palm long." Bananas were introduced to South America by Portuguese sailors who brought them from West Africa in the 16th century.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Southeast Asian banana cultivars, as well as abaca grown for fibers, were introduced to North and Central America by the Spanish from the Philippines, via the Manila galleons.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In the 15th and 16th centuries, Portuguese colonists started banana plantations in the Atlantic Islands, Brazil, and western Africa.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] North Americans began consuming bananas on a small scale at very high prices shortly after the Civil War, though it was only in the 1880s that the food became more widespread.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] As late as the Victorian Era, bananas were not widely known in Europe, although they were available.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The earliest modern plantations originated in Jamaica and the related Western Caribbean Zone, including most of Central America.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Plantation cultivation involved the combination of modern transportation networks of steamships and railroads with the development of refrigeration that allowed more time between harvesting and ripening.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] North American shippers like Lorenzo Dow Baker and Andrew Preston, the founders of the Boston Fruit Company started this process in the 1870s, with the participation of railroad builders like Minor C.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Development led to the multi-national giant corporations like Chiquita and Dole.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] These companies were monopolistic, vertically integrated (controlling growing, processing, shipping and marketing) and usually used political manipulation to build enclave economies (internally self-sufficient, virtually tax exempt, and export-oriented, contributing little to the host economy).
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The vast majority of the world's bananas are cultivated for family consumption or for sale on local markets.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] They are grown in large quantities in India, while many other Asian and African countries host numerous small-scale banana growers who sell at least some of their crop.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Peasants with smallholdings of 1 to 2 acres in the Caribbean produce bananas for the world market, often alongside other crops.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In many tropical countries, the main cultivars produce green (unripe) bananas used for cooking.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Because bananas and plantains produce fruit year-round, they provide a valuable food source during the *hunger season* between harvests of other crops, and are thus important for global food security.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Bananas are propagated asexually from offshoots.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The plant is allowed to produce two shoots at a time; a larger one for immediate fruiting and a smaller "sucker" or "follower" to produce fruit in 6–8 months.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] As a non-seasonal crop, bananas are available fresh year-round.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In global commerce in 2009, by far the most important cultivars belonged to the triploid *Musa acuminata* AAA group of Cavendish group bananas.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Disease is threatening the production of the Cavendish banana worldwide.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] It is unclear if any existing cultivar can replace Cavendish bananas, so various hybridisation and genetic engineering programs are attempting to create a disease-resistant, mass-market banana.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] One such strain that has emerged is the Taiwanese Cavendish or Formosana.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Export bananas are picked green, and ripened in special rooms upon arrival in the destination country.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] These rooms are air-tight and filled with ethylene gas to induce ripening, which mimics the normal production of this gas as a ripening hormone.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Ethylene stimulates the formation of amylase, an enzyme that breaks down starch into sugar, influencing the taste.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Ethylene signals the production of pectinase, a different enzyme which breaks down the pectin between the cells of the banana, causing the banana to soften as it ripens.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The vivid yellow color many consumers in temperate climates associate with bananas is caused by ripening around 18 °C (64 °F), and does not occur in Cavendish bananas ripened in tropical temperatures (over 27 °C (81 °F)), which leaves them green.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Bananas are transported over long distances from the tropics to world markets.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] To obtain maximum shelf life, harvest comes before the fruit is mature.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The fruit requires careful handling, rapid transport to ports, cooling, and refrigerated shipping.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The goal is to prevent the bananas from producing their natural ripening agent, ethylene.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] This technology allows storage and transport for 3–4 weeks at 13 °C (55 °F).
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] On arrival, bananas are held at about 17 °C (63 °F) and treated with a low concentration of ethylene.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] After a few days, the fruit begins to ripen and is distributed for final sale.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Ripe bananas can be held for a few days at home.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] If bananas are too green, they can be put in a brown paper bag with an apple or tomato overnight to speed up the ripening process.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The excessive use of fertilizers contributes greatly to eutrophication in streams and lakes, harming aquatic life, while expanding banana production has led to deforestation.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] As soil nutrients are depleted, more forest is cleared for plantations.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] This causes soil erosion and increases the frequency of flooding.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Voluntary sustainability standards such as Rainforest Alliance and Fairtrade are being used to address some of these issues.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Banana production certified in this way grew rapidly at the start of the 21st century to represent 36% of banana exports by 2016.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] However, such standards are applied mainly in countries which focus on the export market, such as Colombia, Costa Rica, Ecuador, and Guatemala; worldwide they cover only 8–10% of production.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Edible bananas are parthenocarpic (seedless).
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] This is important for their edibility, but the lack of seed production makes breeding difficult.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Furthermore, cultivated bananas are typically triploid (less commonly diploid, and a few tetraploid).
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] They are typically derived from the wild diploid species *M. acuminata* and *M. balbisiana*, although some originate from *M. acuminata* only.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Starting in the 1920s, "pedigree breeding" has been employed to try to generate desirable hybrids.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Existing triploids are bred against diploids, sometimes wild with a desired characteristic, trying to create a tetraploid by combining a haploid gamete from the diploid parent with a (rare) unreduced triploid gamete from the other.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The resulting tetraploid can then be bred against another diploid to produce triploid offspring.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] More recently, the "reproductive breeding" strategy treats diploids with colchicine to produce tetraploid offspring, which can then be bred against a second diploid to produce triploids.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Mutation breeding can be used in this crop.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Aneuploidy is a source of significant variation in allotriploid varieties.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] For one example, it can be a source of TR4 resistance.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Lab protocols have been devised to screen for such aberrations and for possible resulting disease resistances.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Wild *Musa* spp. provide useful resistance genetics, and are vital to breeding for TR4 resistance, as shown in introgressed resistance from wild relatives.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The Honduran Foundation for Agricultural Research has bred a seedless banana that is resistant to both Panama disease and black Sigatoka disease.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The team made use of the fact that "seedless" varieties do rarely produce seeds; they obtained around 15 seeds from some 30,000 cultivated plants, pollinated by hand with pollen from wild Asian bananas.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] As of 2018, bananas are exported in larger volume and to a larger value than any other fruit.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In 2022, world production of bananas and plantains combined was 179 million tonnes, led by India and China with a combined total of 26% of global production.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Other major producers were Uganda, Indonesia, the Philippines, Nigeria and Ecuador.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] As reported for 2013, total world exports were 20 million tonnes of bananas and 859,000 tonnes of plantains.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Ecuador and the Philippines were the leading exporters with 5.4 and 3.3 million tonnes, respectively, and the Dominican Republic was the leading exporter of plantains with 210,350 tonnes.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Banana production is affected by climate change through temperature, water stress, geography, light exposure, pests and disease, and carbon dioxide.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Overall, climate change from 1961 to 2016 suggests that climate change has had a net benefit on banana yields due to rising temperatures, but that these benefits are tapering off due to increased water demand and the challenge of growing companion crops like coffee.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Some major producing countries, notably India and China, are considered 'adaptable' as while they do show potential negative effects of climate change on yields, strong technology-yield trends may mitigate climate-driven yield declines.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Shifting bioclimatic zones in some areas, such as Nepal, mean that banana cultivation may increase in some areas as other crops, such as coffee, suffer the effects of climate change in the same region.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] One study indicated the amount of area suited to banana growing in Nepal will grow by 40% by 2050, with some case studies showing benefit from the agroforestry technique of coffee-banana intercropping.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] As part of these adaptations, "market opportunities for smallholder farmers need to be properly addressed through cooperatives or other such local bodies which secure adequate prices for farmers" (p.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Some banana diseases have spread in area due to climate change – for example, Black Sigatoka has spread from Honduras to Brazil, the Caribbean, and most recently, Florida.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Banana growing in Latin America and the Caribbean are predicted to have an increased risk of infection due to increased spore germination and growth, and wetter crop canopies.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] However, predictions for Brazil suggest that due to reduced humidity, areas favorable to Black Sigatoka may decrease.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Bananas are negatively affected by flooding brought on or made worse by climate change.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Even in areas where drying reduces disease risk, the investment in needed irrigation systems could pressure freshwater resources and thus, "the impact of future climate change on banana production from the perspective of management must consider both the disease and the host" (p.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Also, farmers are limited by resources in drought management activities such as weeding, mulching, irrigation costs, and extra labor (p.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Bananas are damaged by a variety of pests, especially nematodes and insects.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Banana roots are subject to damage from multiple species of parasitic nematodes.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] *Radopholus similis* causes nematode root rot, the most serious nematode disease of bananas in economic terms.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Root-knot is the result of infection by species of *Meloidogyne*, while root-lesion is caused by species of *Pratylenchus*, and spiral nematode root damage is the result of infection by *Helicotylenchus* species.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Among the main insect pests of banana cultivation are two beetles that cause substantial economic losses, the banana borer *Cosmopolites sordidus* and the banana stem weevil *Odoiporus longicollis*.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Other significant pests include aphids and scarring beetles.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Although in no danger of outright extinction, bananas of the Cavendish group, which dominate the global market, are under threat.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] There is a need to enrich banana biodiversity by producing diverse new banana varieties, not just focusing on the Cavendish.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Its predecessor 'Gros Michel', discovered in the 1820s, was similarly dominant but had to be replaced after widespread infections of Panama disease.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Monocropping of Cavendish similarly leaves it susceptible to disease and so threatens both commercial cultivation and small-scale subsistence farming.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Within the data gathered from the genes of hundreds of bananas, the botanist Julie Sardos has found several wild banana ancestors currently unknown to scientists, whose genes could provide a means of defense against banana crop diseases.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Overall, fungal diseases are disproportionately important to small island developing states.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Prior to 1960, almost all commercial banana production centered on the Gros Michel cultivar, which was highly susceptible.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Cavendish was chosen as the replacement for Gros Michel because, among resistant cultivars, it produces the highest quality fruit.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] It requires more care during shipping, and its quality compared to Gros Michel is debated.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Fusarium wilt TR4, a reinvigorated strain of Panama disease, was discovered in 1993.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] This virulent form of Fusarium wilt has destroyed Cavendish plantations in several southeast Asian countries and spread to Australia and India.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] As the soil-based fungi can easily be carried on boots, clothing, or tools, the wilt spread to the Americas despite years of preventive efforts.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Without genetic diversity, Cavendish is highly susceptible to TR4, and the disease endangers its commercial production worldwide.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The only known defense to TR4 is genetic resistance.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] This is conferred either by RGA2, a gene isolated from a TR4-resistant diploid banana, or by the nematode-derived Ced9.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] This may be achieved by genetic modification.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Black sigatoka is a fungal leaf spot disease first observed in Fiji in 1963 or 1964.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] It is caused by the ascomycete *Mycosphaerella fijiensis*.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The disease, also called black leaf streak, has spread to banana plantations throughout the tropics from infected banana leaves used as packing material.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] It affects all main cultivars of bananas and plantains (including the Cavendish cultivars), impeding photosynthesis by blackening parts of the leaves, eventually killing the entire leaf.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Starved for energy, fruit production falls by 50% or more, and the bananas that do grow ripen prematurely, making them unsuitable for export.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The fungus has shown ever-increasing resistance to treatment; spraying with fungicides may be required as often as 50 times a year.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Better strategies, with integrated pest management, are needed.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Banana bunchy top virus is a plant virus of the genus *Babuvirus*, family *Nanonviridae* affecting *Musa* spp.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] (including banana, abaca, plantain and ornamental bananas) and *Ensete* spp. in the family *Musaceae*.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Banana bunchy top disease symptoms include dark green streaks of variable length in leaf veins, midribs and petioles.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Leaves become short and stunted as the disease progresses, becoming 'bunched' at the apex of the plant.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Infected plants may produce no fruit or the fruit bunch may not emerge from the pseudostem.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The virus is transmitted by the banana aphid *Pentalonia nigronervosa* and is widespread in Southeast Asia, Asia, the Philippines, Taiwan, Oceania and parts of Africa.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] There is no cure, but it can be effectively controlled by the eradication of diseased plants and the use of virus-free planting material.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] No resistant cultivars have been found, but varietal differences in susceptibility have been reported.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The commercially important Cavendish subgroup is severely affected.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Banana bacterial wilt is a bacterial disease caused by *Xanthomonas campestris* pv.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] First identified on a close relative of bananas, *Ensete ventricosum*, in Ethiopia in the 1960s, The disease was first seen in Uganda in 2001 affecting all banana cultivars.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Since then it has been diagnosed in Central and East Africa, including the banana growing regions of Rwanda, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Tanzania, Kenya, Burundi, and Uganda.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Given the narrow range of genetic diversity present in bananas and the many threats via biotic (pests and diseases) and abiotic threats (such as drought) stress, conservation of the full spectrum of banana genetic resources is ongoing.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In 2024, the economist Pascal Liu of the FAO described the impact of global warming as an "enormous threat" to the world supply of bananas.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Banana germplasm is conserved in many national and regional gene banks, and at the world's largest banana collection, the International *Musa* Germplasm Transit Centre, managed by Bioversity International and hosted at KU Leuven in Belgium.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Since *Musa* cultivars are mostly seedless, they are conserved by three main methods: *in vivo* (planted in field collections), *in vitro* (as plantlets in test tubes within a controlled environment), and by cryopreservation (meristems conserved in liquid nitrogen at −196 °C).
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Genes from wild banana species are conserved as DNA and as cryopreserved pollen.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Seeds from wild species are sometimes conserved, although less commonly, as they are difficult to regenerate.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In addition, bananas and their crop wild relatives are conserved *in situ*, in the wild natural habitats where they evolved and continue to do so.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Diversity is also conserved in farmers' fields where continuous cultivation, adaptation and improvement of cultivars is often carried out by small-scale farmers growing traditional local cultivars.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] A raw banana (not including the peel) is 75% water, 23% carbohydrates, 1% protein, and contains negligible fat.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] A reference amount of 100 grams (3.5 oz) supplies 89 calories, 24% of the Daily Value of vitamin B6, and moderate amounts of vitamin C, manganese, potassium, and dietary fiber, with no other micronutrients in significant content (table).
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Although bananas are commonly thought to contain exceptional potassium content, their actual potassium content is not high per typical food serving, having only 12% of the Daily Value for potassium (table).
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The potassium-content ranking for bananas among fruits, vegetables, legumes, and many other foods is medium.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Bananas are a staple starch for many tropical populations.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Depending upon cultivar and ripeness, the flesh can vary in taste from starchy to sweet, and texture from firm to mushy.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Both the skin and inner part can be eaten raw or cooked.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The primary component of the aroma of fresh bananas is isoamyl acetate (also known as *banana oil*), which, along with several other compounds such as butyl acetate and isobutyl acetate, is a significant contributor to banana flavor.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Plantains are eaten cooked, often as fritters.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Pisang goreng, bananas fried with batter, is a popular street food in Southeast Asia.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Bananas feature in Philippine cuisine, with desserts like *maruya* banana fritters.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Bananas can be made into fruit preserves.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Banana chips are a snack produced from sliced and fried bananas, such as in Kerala.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Dried bananas are ground to make banana flour.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In Africa, matoke bananas are cooked in a sauce with meat and vegetables such as peanuts or beans to make the breakfast dish katogo.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In Western countries, bananas are used to make desserts such as banana bread.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Banana flowers (also called "banana hearts" or "banana blossoms") are used as a vegetable in South Asian and Southeast Asian cuisine.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] As with artichokes, both the fleshy part of the bracts and the heart are edible.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Banana leaves are large, flexible, and waterproof.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] While generally too tough to actually be eaten, they are often used as ecologically friendly disposable food containers or as "plates" in South Asia and several Southeast Asian countries.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In Indonesian cuisine, banana leaf is employed in cooking methods like pepes and botok; banana leaf packages containing food ingredients and spices are cooked in steam or in boiled water, or are grilled on charcoal.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Certain types of tamales are wrapped in banana leaves instead of corn husks.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In Malaysia, banana leaves are traditionally used as a food wrap for nasi lemak.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] While banana leaves are not an essential ingredient, it imparts a subtle, vegetal aroma that enhances the flavor of the dish.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] When banana leaves are used for steaming or grilling, they protect the food ingredients from burning and add a subtle sweet flavor.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In South India, it is customary to serve traditional food on a banana leaf.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In Tamil Nadu (India), dried banana leaves are used as to pack food and to make cups to hold liquid food items.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The tender core of the banana plant's trunk is also used in South Asian and Southeast Asian cuisine.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Examples include the Burmese dish *mohinga*, and the Filipino dishes *inubaran* and *kadyos, manok, kag ubad*.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Fiber harvested from the pseudostems and leaves of the abacá banana (*Musa textilis*) and other bananas have been used for textiles in the Philippines since ancient times.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Archaeological evidence of cloth-weaving tools like spindle whorls date back to the period between 1000 BC and 500 AD in the Philippines.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] However, the tropical environment and the sparsity of pre-colonial records makes it hard to trace its antiquity.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Nevertheless, abacá bananas are the main source of fibers for traditional textiles still woven among various ethnic groups of the Philippines.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Examples of abacá-based textiles include the *t'nalak*, made by the Tiboli tribe of South Cotabato, and *dagmay*, made by the Bagobo people.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Traditional abacá cloth collected from the Philippines during the Spanish colonial period is found in museum collections around the world, like the Boston Museum of Fine Arts and the Textile Museum of Canada.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The oldest surviving example of textile made from banana fibers is the Banton Burial Cloth recovered from a coffin in the sacred Ipot Cave of Banton, Romblon, Philippines, and dated to around the 13th and 14th centuries.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Aside from indigenous clothing for native Filipinos, *medriñaque* was also used during the colonial era as canvas for sails and for stiffening clothing like skirts, collars, and doublets.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The inner fibers are also used in the making of hats, including the "Manila hats", hammocks, matting, cordage, ropes, coarse twines, and Manila paper.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] By the 19th century, abacá fiber had become one of the most important economic exports of the Philippines.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] They were in demand due to their strength and saltwater-resistance.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Outside the Philippines, abacá was first cultivated on a large scale in Sumatra in 1925 under the Dutch, who had observed its cultivation in the Philippines for cordage since the nineteenth century, followed up by plantings in Central America in 1929 sponsored by the U.S.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] It also was transplanted into India and Guam.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] A similar tradition of weaving banana textiles (from *Musa basjoo* and *Musa balbisiana*) also existed among the non-Han minority groups in southern China since at least the Han Dynasty (202 BC – 220 BC).
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Both fruit-bearing and fibrous banana species have been used.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] This textile tradition along with the banana species *Musa basjoo* (Japanese *bashō*, 芭蕉) was introduced to the Ryukyu Islands of Japan at around the 14th century.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] In the Japanese system of kijōka-bashōfu, leaves and shoots are cut from the plant periodically to ensure softness.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Harvested shoots are first boiled in lye to prepare fibers for yarn-making.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] These banana shoots produce fibers of varying degrees of softness, yielding yarns and textiles with differing qualities for specific uses.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] For example, the outermost fibers of the shoots are the coarsest, and are suitable for tablecloths, while the softest innermost fibers are desirable for kimono and kamishimo.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] This traditional Japanese cloth-making process requires many steps, all performed by hand.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Banana paper can be made either from the bark of the banana plant, mainly for artistic purposes, or from the fibers of the stem and non-usable fruits.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The paper may be hand-made or industrially processed.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The large leaves of bananas are locally used as umbrellas.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Banana peel may have capability to extract heavy metal contamination from river water, similar to other purification materials.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Waste bananas can be used to feed livestock.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] As with all living things, potassium-containing bananas emit radioactivity at low levels occurring naturally from the potassium-40 (K-40) isotope.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] The banana equivalent dose of radiation was developed in 1995 as a simple teaching-tool to educate the public about the natural, small amount of K-40 radiation occurring in everyone and in common foods.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p01] Individuals with a latex allergy may experience a reaction to handling or eating bananas.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] The Edo period poet Matsuo Bashō is named after the Japanese word 芭蕉 (*Bashō*) for the Japanese banana.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] The *Bashō* planted in his garden by a grateful student became a source of inspiration to his poetry, as well as a symbol of his life and home.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] We Have No Bananas" was written by Frank Silver and Irving Cohn and originally released in 1923; for many decades, it was the best-selling sheet music in history.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] Since then the song has been rerecorded several times and has been particularly popular during banana shortages.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] A person slipping on a banana peel has been a staple of physical comedy for generations.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] An American comedy recording from 1910 features a popular character of the time, "Uncle Josh", claiming to describe his own such incident.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] The banana's suggestively phallic shape has been exploited in artworks from Giorgio de Chirico's 1913 painting *The Uncertainty of the Poet* onwards.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] In 2019, an exhibition of Natalia LL's video and set of photographs showing a woman "sucking on a banana" at the National Museum in Warsaw was taken down and the museum's director reprimanded.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] The cover artwork for the 1967 debut album of The Velvet Underground features a banana made by Andy Warhol.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] On the original vinyl LP version, the design allowed the listener to "peel" this banana to find a pink, peeled banana on the inside.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] In 1989, the feminist Guerilla Girls made a screenprint with two bananas, intentionally reminiscent of Warhol's, arranged to form a "0" to answer the question in the artwork, "How many works by women artists were in the Andy Warhol and Tremaine auctions at Sotheby's?".
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] Italian artist Maurizio Cattelan created a 2019 concept art piece titled *Comedian* involving taping a banana to a wall using silver duct tape.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] The piece was exhibited briefly at the Art Basel in Miami before being removed from the exhibition and eaten without permission in another artistic stunt titled *Hungry Artist* by New York artist David Datuna.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] In India, bananas serve a prominent part in many festivals and occasions of Hindus.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] In South Indian weddings, particularly Tamil weddings, banana trees are tied in pairs to form an arch as a blessing to the couple for a long-lasting, useful life.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] In Thailand, it is believed that a certain type of banana plant may be inhabited by a spirit, Nang Tani, a type of ghost related to trees and similar plants that manifests itself as a young woman.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] People often tie a length of colored satin cloth around the pseudostem of the banana plants.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] In Malay folklore, the ghost known as Pontianak is associated with banana plants (*pokok pisang*), and its spirit is said to reside in them during the day.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] In European, British, and Australian sport, throwing a banana at a member of an opposing team has long been used as a form of racial abuse.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-p02] The act, which was commonplace in England in the 1980s, is meant to taunt players of Black African ancestry by equating them to apes or monkeys.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-pudding] It is commonly associated with Southern US cuisine, but it can be found around the country in specific areas.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-pudding] A typical method for making banana pudding is to repeatedly layer the bananas, custard, and wafers into a dish and top with whipped cream or meringue.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-pudding] Over time, the wafers will absorb the custard and the layers will combine, causing the flavors to intermingle.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-pudding] Recipes for banana pudding became very popular in the 1890s across the US, with the sponge cake approach being the most popular.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-pudding] In 1920, the use of vanilla wafers instead of ladyfingers first appeared, first seen in a recipe from Mrs.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-pudding] Laura Kerley in a Bloomington, Illinois local newspaper, *The Pantagraph*.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-pudding] Following the rise in popularity of using wafers, in the 1940s the National Biscuit Company (later known as Nabisco) began printing a recipe for banana pudding on the Nilla Wafers box, whose marketing helped further boost the dessert's acclaim.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-pudding] It is clear that banana pudding did not begin with the strong ties to the Southern US that it maintains today, although there is no consensus on how the Southern identity developed.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-pudding] Some have theorized that it developed naturally through large gatherings such as church picnics, family reunions, and barbecues, because the dessert is easy to scale up, requires no cooking, and keeps well.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-pudding] The National Banana Pudding Festival is held at the Centerville River Park in Centerville, Tennessee.
[src:banana-pudding/banana-pudding] It is a 2-day event held on the first weekend of October.
[src:banana-pudding/banlec] BanLec has a number of similarities to Concanavalin A and binds to mannose-related carbohydrate structures.
[src:banana-pudding/banlec] It was discovered due to its highly immunogenic properties—BanLec induces a strong IgG4 antibody response—and appears to be an important antigen involved in banana allergies.
[src:banana-pudding/banlec] BanLec expression can be induced by the plant hormone methyl jasmonate.
[src:banana-pudding/banlec] BanLec exists as a homodimer of two identical 15 kDa subunits and has also been reported as a tetramer complex.
[src:banana-pudding/banlec] BanLec features strong intersubunit interactions with high levels of hydrogen bonding and water bridges allowing resistance to denaturing when exposed to high temperatures or high concentrations of chaotropes such as guanidium hydrochloride.
[src:banana-pudding/banlec] Crystal structures of BanLec suggest that the lectin has two saccharide binding sites.
[src:banana-pudding/banlec] In 2010, BanLec was reported to be a potent inhibitor of HIV replication.
[src:banana-pudding/banlec] Researchers at the University of Michigan determined that BanLec bound to the HIV-1 envelope protein gp120, which is high in sugar content, inhibiting viral entry into human cells.
[src:banana-pudding/banlec] The researchers suggest that such an inhibitor of HIV infection may find use as a topical treatment, such as a vaginal microbicide, and may be cheaper to produce than current antiviral topical treatments.
